Take my word for it; this is a great site. You can get about 10-15 points per day just from watching YouTube videos. You also get an e-mail from them daily which contains 1, 2, 5, 10 or more points (I have earned 60 points from this over about 3 weeks which is great for doing nothing). They do surveys but I avoid them because I'm not looking to make serious money. They also have a lottery thing - I earned like 10 points on this at one time. You can do it daily a number of times and it's pretty great.

So hell, make an account, fill out your information, watch some YouTube videos and then just let the e-mails roll in. Even if you're not that interested in making serious money, the points from the e-mails alone (as I levelled up, I started to get 5 or 10 points per day as opposed to 1 or 2) acts as like interest.

ex-parrot: you can convert all your database tables to innodb, then use --single-transaction with mysqldump for a lockless live backup ex-parrot: but the beef is in the restore, "nobobdy wants backup. everybody wants restore". ex-parrot: so you might as well have a slave running that is more or less idle or doing dhw quries that are noncritical, ex-parrot: and if the master fails, you switch the clients over to the slave. ex-parrot: (you should be de-slaving (liberating) the slave before that) trelayne: if you have oltp type of work, use innodb. if you have dwh type of work use myisam. ex-parrot: yes, switchover has to be done cleanly. if you dislike replication in mysql another way to do it is to use drbd. trelayne: online transaction processing ex-parrot: drbd is a "raid-1 over the network" type of disk driver ex-parrot: so you have a regular mysql on the active machine, ex-parrot: and disk writes are copied to a second passive machine. ex-parrot: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DRBD ex-parrot: has a nice drawing ex-parrot: then automate the switchover using another piece of software such as heartbeat ex-parrot: it is all nicely integrated ex-parrot: cluster is most likely not working the way you think it works. ex-parrot: you are fine then. most people find the performance aspects of shared-nothing clusters a bit confusing ex-parrot: optimizer in mysql is built to minimize disk seeks. cluster is an in memory database, there is no seek time to avoid. optimizer knows nothing about table fragments in cluster and network latency, ex-parrot: but cluster is very sensitive to network latency. ex-parrot: so the optimizer often makes questionable choices with regard to cluster.

227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: here now cool oh? well, shows what i know :-) btw, what's the plan for actually defining the requirements for things like mouse and key events, is that in dom3 events? as in, the text that says "when a user presses down on a key on the keyboard, the user agent must send a keydown event that..." or whatever would probably make sense to have that in a separate spec, but i'd imagine that e.g. for mouse events it would be the same spec that defines MouseEvent seems independent of host language, since DOM3 Events presumably would work unchanged whether the Document object had any child nodes or not doesn't really understand the concept of "host language" these days seems somewhat anachronistic are we expecting dom3 events to be reused, rather than just implemented as is? reuse in that way sounds scary; i agree that we'd want it to behave uniformly everywhere well presumably we'd want that event to work the same regardless of what the root element happens to be though that would mean defining the xml parser in a more useful way than currently, i guess isn't sure what to do about the dependencies on an xml parser spec in html5 huh i thought SVG fired SVGLoad, not load if it's a 'load' event, how does a UA know how to fire it? maybe this should indeed be handled by the dom3 events spec somehow though really neither xhtml nor svg should be firing the 'load' event, that should just be fired by a generic "xml parsing for scripted uas" spec hm is that defined anywhere? (or that description all there is?) s/or/or is/ well there are no requirements there, for one so nothing testable even if we pretend that the descriptive text is normative, it's also very vague, e.g.: what does "finishes loading the element" mean? what does "after" mean? is the event fired synchronously or asynchronously? what is the target of the event? what exactly are the dependent resources? does it trigger when the element is reinserted? some of the text suggests not, some suggests it is well without violating the w3c process, how will svg 1.2 tiny get to CR if the spec isn't testable? get past CR, i mean apologises for being passive-aggressive anyway, html has taught us that if a technology gets widely deployed, this kind of detail will get locked down, de-facto if not de-jure, and if it's de-facto then it'll be mostly random the mess that people complain about in html is basically all due to the people writing the specs in the past saying "I think some of the questions there are not a big deal, and a reasonable reading of the text would satisfy most developers" re mutation events; what are the options on the table? well that seems like an easy choice then that might help, yeah to make progress on the html5 spec i don't really care what the mutation event spec says, i just need it to be precise so i know how to fiddle with the rules, basically there's some things where we want them to not fire at all and some where we want them to fire in particular ways, and right now i just don't know how to do it well, html5 is supposed to be locked down and done by october i expect to have most of this stuff done by end-of-q2 cool okie dokie i never thought i'd see the day where html5's progress might be tied up waiting on a dependency on another spec :-P cool yeah the non-api parts are being shipped off to an ID the API basically idl block and related requirements i can edit it, there won't be much to it i don't mind where it is, it just needs a home for patent protection i'm happy to continue assuming it's in the htmlwg charter, after all, it's already in the html5 spec at the moment but the last time i did that (Workers) the spec ended up being moved so i figured i'd just check first :-) any help would be greatly appreciated in all likelihood the spec will be done by the time the charter is approved, so if you need a timetable you can put FPWD, LC, and CR all within 3 months of each other as in, three months apart close enough for me! that's probably actually exactly what this was intended for -- i expect that came from the TCPConnection API in WHATWG which is what WebSocket came from aah, cool well, this won't do quite the same as the networking stuff from svg that was raw sockets iirc so there's no draft yet for this? i'm not stepping on anyone's editorship toes or anything? i've no desire to cause more trouble than necessary... cool let me know if/when i should mail anything to the list my plan is to have the websocket text wrapped up by end-of-q1 (and then just watch them painfully go through the ietf and w3c processes) cool, thanks nn

here is a design problem.. we have stateless webservice based business objects with dataacess code.. they want us to take the results from the dataacess and tranform it into strongly typed classes (i.e a workerclass, customerclass ) etc we want to keep the dataacess code to itself and the business code to itself.. for preformance we dont want to return a dataset, and pass that the to business code to transform into its objects so 1) either the dataacess code has to know too much about the specific workerclass, custoemrclass etc.. or the business code has to have access to the datareader (which isn't good either), or in my solution, i had the business objects implement a interface with "setproperty", and therefore the dataacess just reads the data, and calls the specific busienss objects, via the generic interface any other good ways to solve this problem? yep XSL makes perfect sense for that kind of transformation it would, if we werent forced to have these strongly typed classes.. and were allowed to use XML at the sql server level, but no we aren't http://www.karlprosser.com/blogpics/windowsvistapop.JPG ah, its the new PourOnce vista installation technology just pour it on your PC, and the nanotechnology bots will find your harddrive and install vista, pretty impressive really it didnt taste very good though

network replcated packets replicates the same way hosts have been filtering unicast for years (or any frame not addressed to it)

mostly router replicated, but also adds to a host's receive mac filter. the host adds to its filter when it joins a multicast, which notifies the router that the segment needs to be sent those packets. the router receives a multicast packet on one interface, and sends it on any others that need it.

Hixie: not that you can really do anything about it at this point, but amusingly Chromium/Webkit sort of deadlocks if you call executeSql from inside a statement callback, which is the only way to execute a query based on the results of a previous one I think the proliferation of callbacks in Web APIs has got out of control, and certain things are simply impossible if all you have are callback-based APIs 4c681049601b3c374f1d2c0077c99049: yes, I'm reducing it to the minimal testcase now still, any API that could possibly ever be called from an event listener should have a sync version, or else things go wrong sure, but there's openDatabaseSync already, so that argument doesn't really fly in the specific case of webSQL oh, it doesn't really say it in the spec that I've noticed rereads b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: but transactions are already run async so if you add another level of executeSql working async, it becomes quite unmanageable b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: ah, right, WorkerUtilsDatabase b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: one way to alleviate it a bit would be to introduce checkpoints / barriers that could be inserted optionally and would essentially put the caller to sleep until the results are available so transaction.barrier() would make sure all transaction steps queued until now have been performed b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: it doesn't really need to be exposed in the language it would if your callback stuffed the result in a known location, which is not hard to do with closures, which JS thankfully does have ah, you're looking at it from the other side I mean more like this: function myTransaction(tx) { var result; tx.executeSql("...",[], function(tx, r) { result = r }); tx.checkpoint(); alert(result) } b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: related is http://chumsley.org/jwacs/ which is a dialect with continuations that transforms to regular JS though I don't believe you can actually use it to fix things like "can't use any async APIs from inside an event listener"

If those two methods are deleted then then the [Widgets-Updates] ref can be deleted too? Why remove the related requirement? for XHR that is? in the abstract e.g. for defining a useful "Widget UA", it is a reasonable requirement It just doesn't appear to be a requirement that is satisfied by A+E spec In a "Widget User Agent" spec, I presume Did you say OMTP is defining such a spec? :)

I think CSS animations are for simple things, like mouse overs, and to assist Javascript in most needs of UI interaction. So, if you want a nice animation after an ajax call, CSS animations are great. Page transitions, more interactive forms... there is a great playground around that It's simple First you make too classes for the start and final state .loading {height:20px;background-image:url(l.gif);} and .loaded {height:auto;background-image:none;} would do. via javascript is trivial to set this classes, right? yup so you tell css to animate thease changes: .box {transition: height 800ms;} sorry for the delay, I was checking the syntax its a class that don't change along the process... <div class="box"></div> on page load, then you trigger your ajax and set the class <div class="box loading"></div> and finally wen content loads <div class="box loaded">content here</div> just an example yup the box {transition: height 800ms;} tells the engine that whatever happens to the height of the elements with a box class, instead of changing immediately, should change by transition you can have many properties like opacity, width, height, and so on and on... you can box {transition: all 800ms;} and change many properties at once Here is a great example: http://hakim.se/inc/components/slideshow/#/ in firefox, just opacity animates, but when you open this one in Safari you will go "WOOOWW" because Safari has a lot of 3D CSS transitions that firefox have not implemented yet 105bbb3c1ce4cdd44a2521c19ab5f155: ^ this one (only safari too) is really impressive http://m.madebycanvas.com/
